# Brief: <Piece Title>

A short statement of what this brief is and what the drafter should produce: a
concept proposal (`installation.tex`) compiling under XeLaTeX, following the
11-section template, scoring against the 9-dimension rubric.

## Premise (section 1)

One paragraph: what the piece is, where the visitor stands, and the single
argument it makes. This becomes the Premise callout — it must be legible
without a wall text.

## The Frame (section 2)

The conceptual / cultural / legal anchor the piece is built around, and the
tension it exposes. Name the anchor (a text, a doctrine, a phenomenon, a
tradition).

## The Visitor's Hour (section 3)

The choreography of the encounter as a timeline: threshold → approach →
encounter → exit, with rough durations.

## Architecture (section 4)

The principal form, its scale and geometry, where it sits, and the
architectural lineage. Give dimensions where you can — the reviewer scores
"described vs. designed" on this section.

## The Light / Sensory Language (section 5)

The sensory medium the piece speaks in (light, sound, material, scent,
temperature) and the distinct sensory voices within it.

## The Ritual Act / Participation Mechanic (section 6 — participatory only)

The act the piece asks of the visitor: what they do, what they give up or take
on, and why the act is the point.

## The Consent Structure (section 7 — participatory only)

How participation is chosen and how it is declined without penalty.

## Safety Without Surveillance (section 8 — participatory only)

The safety promise and the constraint the concept places on how safety may be
achieved. Passive sensing, failsafe behavior, staffing.

## References & Lineage (section 9)

Art-historical / architectural precedents the work is in conversation with.

## Budget & Operations (section 10)

What dominates capital cost, what dominates operating cost, expected
throughput, and the plausible commissioning paths. Planning ranges, not bids.

## Open Decisions (section 11)

The unresolved choices, tracked honestly — the choices a commissioning
conversation would need to settle.
